<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>25792</anchor> <rss>anon.200.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Proof</taxon> <addr>anon.200</addr>  <route>anon.200.xml</route>    </frontmatter> <mainmatter>
  <p>Let <tex>i,j</tex> be two <link href="jms-001M.xml" type="local" addr="jms-001M" title="The positive elements of a pointed dcpo">positive</link> elements of <tex>I</tex>; we must show that there exists a positive element <tex>k \in  I</tex> such that <tex>i \sqsubseteq  k</tex> and <tex>j \sqsubseteq  k</tex>. This follows immediately from the directedness of <tex>I</tex> and <link href="jms-0029.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0029" title="Positivity is upward-closed">the fact that positivity is monotone</link>.</p>
</mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>25793</anchor> <rss>jms-0028.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-0028</addr>  <route>jms-0028.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>2</month> <day>16</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The positive part of a semidirected subset is semidirected</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>I \subseteq  A</tex> be a semidirected subset of a <link href="jms-001S.xml" type="local" addr="jms-001S" title="Pointed dcpo">pointed</link> dcpo <tex>A</tex>; then the intersection <tex>I  \cap  A^+</tex> is semidirected, where <tex>A^+</tex> is the <link href="jms-001P.xml" type="local" addr="jms-001P" title="The subdcpo spanned by positive elements">subdcpo spanned by positive elements</link>.</p>
 
   
   
 
</mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>25794</anchor> <rss>jms-0029.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Lemma</taxon> <addr>jms-0029</addr>  <route>jms-0029.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>2</month> <day>16</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Positivity is upward-closed</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>i \sqsubseteq  j</tex> in a <link href="jms-001S.xml" type="local" addr="jms-001S" title="Pointed dcpo">pointed</link> dcpo <tex>A</tex> such that <tex>i</tex> is <link href="jms-001M.xml" type="local" addr="jms-001M" title="The positive elements of a pointed dcpo">positive</link>; then <tex>j</tex> is <link href="jms-001M.xml" type="local" addr="jms-001M" title="The positive elements of a pointed dcpo">positive</link>.</p>
 
   
   <tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="false" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>25795</anchor> <rss>anon.199.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Proof</taxon> <addr>anon.199</addr>  <route>anon.199.xml</route>    </frontmatter> <mainmatter>
  <p>Fixing semidirected <tex>J \subseteq  A</tex> such that <tex>j \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup {J}</tex>, we must show that <tex>J</tex> is inhabited. This follows from our assumption that <tex>i</tex> is positive becuase <tex>i \sqsubseteq  j \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup {J}</tex>.</p>
</mainmatter> </tree>
 
</mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>25796</anchor> <rss>jms-001M.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-001M</addr>  <route>jms-001M.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>2</month> <day>14</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The positive elements of a pointed dcpo</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An element <tex>u</tex> of a <link href="jms-001S.xml" type="local" addr="jms-001S" title="Pointed dcpo">pointed</link> dpco <tex>A</tex> is called <em>positive</em> when for any semidirected subset <tex>I \subseteq  A</tex>, if <tex>u \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup {I}</tex> then <tex>I</tex> is inhabited. We will write <tex>\mathsf { pos } \, {u}</tex> to mean that <tex>u</tex> is a positive element.</p><p>(This is adapted from <link href="johnstone-1984.xml" type="local" addr="johnstone-1984" title="Open locales and exponentiation">Johnstone</link>’s definition of positive elements of frames to the case of dcpos by <link href="dejong-2023-thesis.xml" type="local" addr="dejong-2023-thesis" title="Domain theory in constructive and predicative univalent foundations">Tom de Jong</link>.)</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>